  "prompt": "3. Who decides who will manage the company and how?",
  "response": "The management of a company is typically decided by its board of directors, which is elected by the shareholders. Here\u2019s how the process generally works:\n\n1. **Shareholders**: The owners of the company\u2019s shares (shareholders) have the ultimate authority in deciding the composition of the board of directors during annual general meetings (AGMs) or special meetings.\n\n2. **Board of Directors**: The board is responsible for overseeing the company\u2019s management. Members of the board are usually elected by the shareholders. They make decisions on strategic direction and key policies and hire, assess, and if necessary, replace the company's executive management.\n\n3. **Executive Management**: The board of directors typically appoints senior executives, such as the CEO, CFO, and other key positions. These executives are responsible for the day-to-day operations of the company.\n\n4. **Nomination Committees**: Many boards have nomination or governance committees that identify and recommend candidates for the board. These committees may consider various factors, including skills, experience, and diversity.\n\n5. **Performance Evaluations**: The board assesses the performance of the management team periodically, often relying on metrics and benchmarks, to ensure that the company is being managed effectively and is meeting its strategic goals.\n\nIn summary, the governance structure of a company ensures that the management team is chosen and managed by the board of directors, who are ultimately accountable to the shareholders.",
